# ADR-0002 – Use Ports and Adapters

**Status:** Accepted

**Date:** 2026-07-22

---

# Context

Nordschleifen Coach integrates with several external systems:

* Assetto Corsa Competizione
* Local file system
* SQLite database
* AI providers
* Future dashboards and APIs

These technologies may change over time. The core business logic should remain independent of any specific implementation.

Without a clear boundary between the application and external systems, changes in infrastructure would directly affect business logic.

---

# Decision

The project adopts the **Ports and Adapters (Hexagonal Architecture)** pattern to isolate business logic from external technologies.

Communication between the application and the outside world will occur only through well-defined interfaces (ports). Concrete implementations (adapters) will provide the technical behavior.

---

# Architecture

The application defines the required interfaces.

Examples of outbound ports:

* TelemetryRepository
* SessionRepository
* AICoach
* FeatureStore
* TrainingPlanRepository

Examples of inbound ports:

* ImportTelemetry
* AnalyzeSession
* CompareSessions
* GenerateTrainingPlan

Adapters implement these interfaces for specific technologies.

Examples:

* ACCTelemetryCollector
* SQLiteSessionRepository
* OpenAICoach
* FileSystemTelemetryRepository

---

# Dependency Rule

Interfaces are defined by the application layer.

Infrastructure implements these interfaces.

Business logic never depends on concrete implementations.

```text
Application
     │
     ▼
 Port (Interface)
     ▲
     │
Infrastructure Adapter
```

---

# Consequences

## Advantages

* External systems can be replaced without changing business logic.
* Infrastructure components are independently testable.
* Mock implementations simplify unit testing.
* New simulators and AI providers can be integrated with minimal changes.

## Trade-offs

* Additional interfaces increase the number of files.
* Slightly more boilerplate code.
* Requires discipline when introducing new dependencies.

These trade-offs are acceptable because modularity and long-term maintainability are primary project goals.

---

# Alternatives Considered

## Direct infrastructure access

Rejected because it tightly couples business logic to implementation details.

## Service locator pattern

Rejected because dependencies become implicit and harder to test.

## Global utility classes

Rejected because they reduce modularity and make future extensions more difficult.

---

# Decision Outcome

All communication between the application and external technologies shall occur through ports and adapters.

The application layer defines interfaces.

Infrastructure provides implementations.

The domain and application layers remain independent of external technologies.
